In ultra-low latency trading systems, the standard approach for passing messages (like market data ticks or normalized order structs) between threads—such as from a network I/O thread to a strategy thread—is a Single-Producer Single-Consumer (SPSC) Lock-Free Ring Buffer.

To make it truly "ultra-low latency," we must go beyond just avoiding std::mutex. We have to actively manage the CPU cache and memory model.

Here is a production-grade implementation in modern C++ (C++11/14/17) with the necessary optimizations for high-frequency trading (HFT).

The Architecture of an HFT Queue
To achieve sub-microsecond latency, this implementation focuses on three critical optimizations:

No Dynamic Memory Allocation: The buffer size is fixed at compile time. There are no new or delete calls on the critical path.

Preventing False Sharing: CPU cache lines are typically 64 bytes. If the producer's write index and the consumer's read index sit on the same cache line, the CPU cores will constantly invalidate each other's L1 cache (cache ping-pong). We use alignas to pad these variables into separate cache lines.

Cached Indices: We cache the atomic indices locally. The producer only checks the atomic read_idx when its local copy says the queue is full. This drastically reduces the atomic traffic across the CPU interconnect.

Relaxed Memory Ordering: We avoid std::memory_order_seq_cst (which emits heavy CPU fences) and strictly use Acquire-Release semantics.

The C++ Implementation
C++
#include <atomic>
#include <cstddef>
#include <type_traits>
#include <stdexcept>

// Hardware cache line size (64 bytes for most x86/ARM architectures)
constexpr std::size_t CACHE_LINE_SIZE = 64;

template <typename T, std::size_t Capacity>
class UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue {
    // Enforce power of 2 for extremely fast modulo arithmetic (bitwise AND)
    static_assert(Capacity > 0 && ((Capacity & (Capacity - 1)) == 0), 
                  "Capacity must be a power of 2");
                  
    // In HFT, we only pass PODs (Plain Old Data) through queues to avoid 
    // complex constructor/destructor overhead and exception handling on the critical path.
    static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable<T>::value, 
                  "Queue elements must be trivially copyable for ultra-low latency");

private:
    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    // PRODUCER STATE (Exclusively accessed by the Producer Thread)
    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    alignas(CACHE_LINE_SIZE) std::atomic<std::size_t> write_idx_{0};
    std::size_t cached_read_idx_{0}; // Avoids constantly loading the atomic read_idx_

    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    // CONSUMER STATE (Exclusively accessed by the Consumer Thread)
    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    alignas(CACHE_LINE_SIZE) std::atomic<std::size_t> read_idx_{0};
    std::size_t cached_write_idx_{0}; // Avoids constantly loading the atomic write_idx_

    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    // SHARED DATA (The Ring Buffer itself)
    // ---------------------------------------------------------
    alignas(CACHE_LINE_SIZE) T buffer_[Capacity];

    // Helper for fast modulo
    static constexpr std::size_t MASK = Capacity - 1;

public:
    UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue() = default;
    ~UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue() = default;

    // Delete copy and move to prevent accidental copying of atomic states
    UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue(const UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue&) = delete;
    UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue& operator=(const UltraLowLatencySPSCQueue&) = delete;

    /**
     * Push an item into the queue.
     * Called strictly by the PRODUCER thread.
     * Returns true on success, false if the queue is full.
     */
    bool push(const T& item) {
        const std::size_t current_write = write_idx_.load(std::memory_order_relaxed);
        const std::size_t next_write = current_write + 1;

        // Check if full: Is the write pointer about to lap the cached read pointer?
        if (next_write - cached_read_idx_ > Capacity) {
            // Queue *might* be full. Update our cached read index from the actual atomic.
            // We use memory_order_acquire to ensure we see all consumer reads up to this point.
            cached_read_idx_ = read_idx_.load(std::memory_order_acquire);
            
            // Check again with the fresh data
            if (next_write - cached_read_idx_ > Capacity) {
                return false; // Queue is truly full
            }
        }

        // Write the data. MASK ensures we wrap around the ring buffer automatically.
        buffer_[current_write & MASK] = item;

        // Publish the new write index.
        // memory_order_release ensures the data write above "happens-before" 
        // the consumer sees the updated write_idx_.
        write_idx_.store(next_write, std::memory_order_release);
        
        return true;
    }

    /**
     * Pop an item from the queue.
     * Called strictly by the CONSUMER thread.
     * Returns true on success, false if the queue is empty.
     */
    bool pop(T& item) {
        const std::size_t current_read = read_idx_.load(std::memory_order_relaxed);

        // Check if empty: Have we caught up to the cached write pointer?
        if (current_read == cached_write_idx_) {
            // Queue *might* be empty. Update our cached write index from the actual atomic.
            // memory_order_acquire ensures we see all producer writes up to this point.
            cached_write_idx_ = write_idx_.load(std::memory_order_acquire);
            
            // Check again with the fresh data
            if (current_read == cached_write_idx_) {
                return false; // Queue is truly empty
            }
        }

        // Read the data.
        item = buffer_[current_read & MASK];

        // Publish the new read index.
        // memory_order_release ensures the data read above "happens-before"
        // the producer sees the updated read_idx_ (so it doesn't overwrite it too early).
        read_idx_.store(current_read + 1, std::memory_order_release);
        
        return true;
    }
};
Key Technical Takeaways
The Capacity - 1 Bitwise Trick: By enforcing that Capacity is a power of 2 (e.g., 1024, 2048), we completely eliminate the expensive modulo operator %. Instead, current_write & (Capacity - 1) performs the wrap-around instantly at the CPU register level.

Free-Running Indices: Notice that the write_idx_ and read_idx_ do not wrap around; they just increment forever (until a 64-bit unsigned integer overflows, which takes hundreds of years). The wrap-around is only applied when accessing the array (current_read & MASK). This simplifies the full/empty mathematical checks.

The Cached Index Optimization: In a naive lock-free queue, the producer does read_idx_.load() on every single push. This forces the CPU cache line containing read_idx_ to bounce across the L3 interconnect on every iteration. By using cached_read_idx_, the producer only hits the interconnect when it thinks the queue is full. During normal operation (where consumer keeps pace with producer), the atomic checks drop to near zero.
